ies and Policies -- tChapter 9. Studying Writing Across EFL Contexts: Looking Back and Moving Forward -- tChapter 10. Training for Writing or Training for Reality? Challenges Facing EFL Writing Teachers and Students in Language Teacher Education Programs -- tPart 3. Coda -- tChapter 11. Bibliography of Sources on Foreign Language Writing -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book represents the most comprehensive account to date of foreign language (FL) writing. Its basic aim is to reflect critically on where the field is now and where it needs need to go next in the exploration of FL writing at the levels of theory, research, and pedagogy, hence the two parts of the book: 'Looking back' and 'Looking ahead'. The chapters in Part I offer accounts of both the inquiry process followed and the main insights gained in various long-term research programs. The chapters in Part 2 contribute a retrospective analysis of the available empirical research and of professional experiences in an attempt to move forward. The book invites the reader to step back and rethink seemingly well established knowledge about L2 writing in light of what is known about writing in FL contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teaching. 0aRhetoricxStudy and teaching. 0aSecond language acquisition. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Psycholinguistics.2bisacsh  aFL writing.  aL2 writing.  aSLA.  aSecond Language Acquisition.  aforeign language learning.  aforeign language writing.  asecond language learning.  awriting in a 2nd language.1 aCasanave, Christine Pearson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCelaya, M. Luz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu